\n\nTC0 can be characterized in terms of #AC0, the class of functions computed by constant-depth polynomial-size arithmetic circuits of unbounded fan-in addition and multiplication gates. A language A is in TC0 if and only if there is a #AC0 function f and a number k such that x∈A⇔f(x)=2|x|k.\n\nTC0 can be simulated by constant-depth arithmetic circuits, with a single threshold gate.\n\n## Conversion Between Boolean and Arithmetic Circuits\n\nAnother restatement of this characterization is that TC0 can be simulated by constant-depth arithmetic circuits, with a single threshold gate. The paper by Agrawal, Allender, and Datta discusses converting Boolean circuits to arithmetic circuits over finite fields involving modular operations.\n\n## Modular Arithmetic and Complexity\n\nFor languages in ACC0, the process involves finding a prime p of the form am + 1 and replacing all Modm gates with Modp−1 gates. AND gates can be replaced by product gates modulo p, since the value of each gate is Boolean.\n\nThe research establishes fundamental connections between Boolean threshold complexity and arithmetic circuit complexity over finite fields, with polynomial size maintained throughout these conversions.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"1b6d5b80-eb43-4fc2-bb21-7877d781f00e","timestamp":"2026-04-04T16:39:46.825Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"10aa06ab-b465-4579-bc35-99d7c378cbd3","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"9a4d0a1c-3aab-4791-8f3d-2b88c6fa29b8","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"iridescent-kindling-sparkle"}
