    {"parentUuid":"ac4e47ec-d40e-4143-8ccd-957ab04128f8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"692796b1-864b-4e7d-b7d2-59cccd6adeda","agentId":"aa44784d08165fb3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012Xt5Gws26pLhpyXtBs3X77","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Andrews Wigderson SIAM 2025 polynomial GCD constant depth \"open problems\" conclusions matrix determinant\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Constant-Depth Arithmetic Circuits for Linear Algebra Problems | SIAM Journal on Computing\",\"url\":\"https://doi.org/10.1137/24M1708085\"},{\"title\":\"Constant-depth circuits for polynomial GCD over any characteristic\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.23220\"},{\"title\":\"[2404.10839] Constant-Depth Arithmetic Circuits for Linear Algebra Problems\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.10839\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] Constant-Depth Arithmetic Circuits for Linear Algebra Problems | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Constant-Depth-Arithmetic-Circuits-for-Linear-Andrews-Wigderson/2043d03b259bc5d470c8d630fc09b747871515b4\"},{\"title\":\"ECCC - TR25-171\",\"url\":\"https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2025/171/\"},{\"title\":\"[2506.23220] Constant-depth circuits for polynomial GCD over any characteristic\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.23220\"},{\"title\":\"ECCC - TR25-085\",\"url\":\"https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/report/2025/085/\"},{\"title\":\"ECCC - Robert Andrews\",\"url\":\"https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/author/1330/\"},{\"title\":\"Generalized algorithms for the approximate matrix\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1907.13101\"},{\"title\":\"Determinant: Old Algorithms, New Insights | SIAM Journal on Discrete Mathematics\",\"url\":\"https://epubs.siam.org/doi/10.1137/S0895480198338827\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found the Andrews-Wigderson paper on constant-depth arithmetic circuits. Here's what I found:\n\n## Main Results\n\nAndrews and Wigderson design polynomial-size, constant-depth (AC₀) arithmetic formulae for the greatest common divisor (GCD) of two polynomials as well as the related problems of the discriminant, resultant, and Bézout coefficients; squarefree decomposition; and the inversion of structured matrices, such as Sylvester and Bézout matrices.\n\nTheir GCD algorithm extends to any number of polynomials, and previously, the best-known arithmetic formulae for these problems required superpolynomial size regardless of depth.\n\n## Key Technical Approach\n\nThese results are based on new algorithmic techniques to compute various symmetric functions in the roots of polynomials and to manipulate the multiplicities of these roots without having access to them. They extend these techniques to problems whose inputs are multivariate polynomials, which are represented by constant-depth arithmetic circuits.\n\n## Publication Information\n\nThe paper was published in the SIAM Journal on Computing in 2025 and is also referenced as appearing in the 2024 IEEE 65th Annual Symposium on Foundations of Computer Science (FOCS).\n\nThe search results indicate this is a significant contribution to understanding the parallel complexity of fundamental algebraic problems, particularly demonstrating that polynomial GCD computation can be done efficiently in constant depth with only polynomial size overhead.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"c3546fb6-c2e4-47c4-bdee-2c0c70271d75","timestamp":"2026-04-04T16:39:57.526Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ac4e47ec-d40e-4143-8ccd-957ab04128f8","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"9a4d0a1c-3aab-4791-8f3d-2b88c6fa29b8","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"iridescent-kindling-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"c3546fb6-c2e4-47c4-bdee-2c0c70271d75","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aa44784d08165fb3d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01YAQZr32fTUMiRsPqUMTLBM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have comprehensive information. Here is my report.\n\n---\n\n## Research Report: Andrews-Wigderson FOCS 2024 and Implications for pi(x)\n\n### 1. What Exactly Is Proven\n\nAndrews and Wigderson (arXiv:2404.10839, FOCS 2024, published in SIAM J. Computing 2025) prove that the following problems can be computed by **polynomial-size, constant-depth arithmetic circuits** (arithmetic AC^0) over fields of characteristic 0 or sufficiently large positive characteristic:\n\n- **Polynomial GCD** (univariate, extending to any number of polynomials, and to multivariate)\n- **Discriminant**\n- **Resultant**\n- **Bezout coefficients**\n- **Squarefree decomposition**\n- **Inversion of structured matrices** (Sylvester and Bezout matrices)\n\nPreviously, the best arithmetic formulae for all these problems required **super-polynomial size** regardless of depth. The key technique: computing symmetric functions in the roots of polynomials and manipulating root multiplicities without explicit access to the roots.\n\n**Important caveat on the model:** These are *arithmetic* circuits over a field F, using {+, x, /} gates with unbounded fan-in, plus a \"select\" gate for branching on zero-tests. This is NOT the same as Boolean circuits.\n\n### 2. Does the Paper Address Matrix Powering?\n\n**No, not directly.** The paper discusses:\n- Determinant computation (noting it requires super-polynomial size in arithmetic AC^0, proven by Limaye-Srinivasan-Tavenas 2021)\n- Matrix inversion for structured matrices (Sylvester, Bezout)\n- Notes that 2x2 iterated matrix product is AC^0-hard\n\nBut **matrix powering** (computing M^n) is not addressed. This is relevant because the project's existing analysis (`/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/novel/tc0_matrix_powering_reduction.md`) identifies growing-dimension matrix powering as the precise bottleneck for putting PRIMES in TC^0.\n\n### 3. Could These Linear Algebra Primitives Help Compute pi(x)?\n\n**The short answer is: probably not directly, due to fundamental model mismatches.** Here is the detailed analysis:\n\n**The model mismatch problem:** Andrews-Wigderson work over *fields* (characteristic 0 or large characteristic). The AKS primality test operates over **Z_n[x]/(x^r - 1)**, which is a *ring*, not a field (Z_n has zero divisors when n is composite -- which is exactly the interesting case for primality testing). The GCD result fundamentally relies on field properties (division, root structure, characteristic assumptions).\n\n**Even if we could bridge the field/ring gap**, the connection to pi(x) would require:\n1. Put PRIMES in TC^0 (or similar low-complexity class)\n2. Sum the characteristic function over all k <= x\n\nStep 2 is fine (threshold counting is in TC^0). Step 1 is the bottleneck.\n\n### 4. Specifically: Could Constant-Depth Polynomial GCD Help AKS?\n\nThe AKS test checks: gcd((x+a)^n - x^n - a, x^r - 1) in Z_n[x].\n\n**Three critical obstacles prevent direct application of Andrews-Wigderson:**\n\n**(a) Field vs. Ring:** Andrews-Wigderson compute GCD over a *field* F[x]. AKS needs GCD over Z_n[x], where Z_n is NOT a field. The paper's techniques (symmetric functions in roots, root multiplicity manipulation) rely fundamentally on working over a field where polynomials factor cleanly.\n\n**(b) The GCD is not the bottleneck anyway:** In AKS, computing gcd((x+a)^n - x^n - a, x^r - 1) is easy -- x^r - 1 is known, and the GCD just means \"reduce mod x^r - 1.\" The actual bottleneck is computing **(x+a)^n mod (x^r - 1, n)**, which is matrix powering (an r x r companion matrix raised to the n-th power mod n). This is the growing-dimension MPOW problem identified in your existing analysis.\n\n**(c) Characteristic restriction:** Even the follow-up paper (arXiv:2506.23220, extending to arbitrary characteristic) requires the field to be \"sufficiently large.\" Working mod n for varying n does not fit this framework.\n\n**Bottom line:** The polynomial GCD being in arithmetic AC^0 does not help with AKS, because (i) it's the wrong algebraic setting (fields vs. rings), (ii) GCD isn't the hard part of AKS -- exponentiation is, and (iii) arithmetic AC^0 does not directly translate to Boolean TC^0.\n\n### 5. Relationship Between \"Arithmetic AC^0\" and Boolean TC^0\n\nThis is a subtle and important distinction:\n\n- **Arithmetic AC^0** (denoted AC^0_F): constant-depth, polynomial-size circuits using {+, x, /} over a field F with unbounded fan-in. Computes *polynomials/rational functions* over F.\n\n- **Boolean TC^0**: constant-depth, polynomial-size circuits using AND, OR, NOT, and THRESHOLD gates over {0,1}.\n\n**Key relationships (Agrawal-Allender-Datta 2000):**\n- TC^0 = P^{AC^0} = the class of languages decidable by a polynomial-time machine with an AC^0 oracle\n- TC^0 can be simulated by constant-depth arithmetic circuits (over Z) with a single threshold gate\n- A language is in TC^0 iff it equals the preimage of 2^{|x|^k} under some #AC^0 function\n\n**The critical gap:** Arithmetic AC^0 over a field and #AC^0 (arithmetic circuits over the integers computing a *number*) are different models. Andrews-Wigderson's results are over fields; converting them to Boolean TC^0 results requires:\n1. Replacing field operations with integer/modular operations\n2. Handling bit-level representation\n3. The conversion adds at most O(log* n) depth (known result), so arithmetic depth-d becomes Boolean depth O(d * log* n), which is still constant -- BUT only if the arithmetic circuit works over Z (integers), not over abstract fields with division\n\n**Also relevant:** Any arithmetic circuit over Z of depth d can be converted to a Boolean circuit of depth O(d * log* n). So if the GCD could be computed in arithmetic AC^0 *over the integers* (which Andrews-Wigderson do NOT claim), it would yield Boolean AC^0 up to log* factors.\n\n### 6. Follow-Up Work (2024-2026)\n\nOne notable follow-up found:\n\n- **arXiv:2506.23220** -- \"Constant-depth circuits for polynomial GCD over any characteristic.\" Extends Andrews-Wigderson to fields of *any* sufficiently large characteristic (removing the restriction to char 0 or large char). Uses closure of constant-depth algebraic circuits under factorization. Still over fields, so the same limitations apply for our purposes.\n\n- **arXiv:2505.00730** (April 2025) -- A circulant matrix-based primality test inspired by AKS's cyclotomic constructions, leveraging eigenvalue computations. Claims O~(log^6 n) bounds with potential for parallelization, but details unclear from search results alone.\n\n- The Andrews-Wigderson paper was published in **SIAM Journal on Computing** (2025), doi:10.1137/24M1708085, indicating peer-reviewed acceptance.\n\n### Summary Assessment\n\nAndrews-Wigderson is an important result in algebraic complexity theory, but it does **not** help with computing pi(x) for the following reasons:\n\n1. It operates over fields, not the rings Z_n needed for AKS\n2. Polynomial GCD is not the bottleneck in AKS -- matrix powering is\n3. The arithmetic-to-Boolean conversion is nontrivial and requires working over integers\n4. The paper does not address matrix powering or determinant computation (the determinant is actually *hard* for arithmetic AC^0)\n\nThe existing project analysis in `/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research/novel/tc0_matrix_powering_reduction.md` correctly identifies growing-dimension matrix powering as the precise bottleneck, and Andrews-Wigderson does not touch this problem. The frontier remains exactly where it was: can MPOW with k = O(polylog(n)) growing dimensions be done in TC^0?\n\nSources:\n- [Andrews-Wigderson, arXiv:2404.10839](https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.10839)\n- [Andrews-Wigderson, SIAM J. Computing 2025](https://doi.org/10.1137/24M1708085)\n- [Follow-up: GCD over any characteristic, arXiv:2506.23220](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.23220)\n- [Agrawal-Allender-Datta: On TC0, AC0, and Arithmetic Circuits](https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/On-TC0,-AC0,-and-Arithmetic-Circuits-Agrawal-Allender/b8fd47edc73c873dc65e23bd2ae9e806c74dca24)\n- [TC0 vs NC1 conjecture](https://www.emergentmind.com/open-problems/tc0-vs-nc1-circuit-complexity-conjecture)\n- [Andrews at ECCC](https://eccc.weizmann.ac.il/author/1330/)"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":932,"cache_read_input_tokens":28730,"output_tokens":2340,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":932},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CZj4XzSCAJS6KsW1mv45Y","type":"assistant","uuid":"61724a04-b8b2-45e6-9ef3-4ccc6014f7d3","timestamp":"2026-04-04T16:40:53.370Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"9a4d0a1c-3aab-4791-8f3d-2b88c6fa29b8","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"iridescent-kindling-sparkle"}
    
