    {"parentUuid":"23288070-2ed4-46e2-ac00-6bc95eee69da","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"692796b1-864b-4e7d-b7d2-59cccd6adeda","agentId":"ac31b9f8e30a62569","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QpKRsVyBDAUkuyr2FPMRZC","type":"tool_result","content":"# Fejér-Kernel Prime Indicators - Summary\n\n**Title:** \"Fejér-Kernel Prime Indicators\"\n\n**Author:** Sebastian Fuchs\n\n**Abstract Summary:**\nThe paper constructs a smooth mathematical function that indicates primes. For integers n≥2, the function equals zero precisely for odd primes (with the value positive for 2). The construction uses the Fejér identity applied to trial division methods. Smooth variants are developed with connections to divisor functions.\n\n**Main Claims about Prime Detection:**\n- A continuously differentiable function is constructed where \"ℰP(n)=0 holds exactly for odd primes\" for integers\n- No claims are made beyond integer inputs\n- The author explicitly states: \"No assertion is made beyond integer input, and no statements are claimed about the prime number theorem or zero distributions\"\n\n**Complexity Notes:**\nThe submission history indicates \"v3: explicit jump formula and brief complexity notes added,\" though specific complexity details aren't elaborated in this abstract view.\n\n**Regarding Authorship:**\nBased solely on the content provided, Sebastian Fuchs is the sole author listed. There is no information about a \"TG kernel paper\" or other co-authored works in this excerpt, so I cannot determine if this matches other research."}]},"uuid":"33726432-ceb5-4736-aed4-60bb1a17ba4d","timestamp":"2026-04-04T16:41:07.294Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"23288070-2ed4-46e2-ac00-6bc95eee69da","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"9a4d0a1c-3aab-4791-8f3d-2b88c6fa29b8","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"iridescent-kindling-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"2331dbad-dcf6-4c86-9812-d6f64cbb2811","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"692796b1-864b-4e7d-b7d2-59cccd6adeda","agentId":"ac31b9f8e30a62569","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0178iBue3feaESj58orDQ7yh","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Kilictas Alpay prime counting TG kernel previous papers analytic number theory\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"[2506.22634] A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.22634\"},{\"title\":\"[PDF] A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting | Semantic Scholar\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/A-Rigorous-Error-Bound-for-the-TG-Kernel-in-Prime-Kilictas-Alpay/ea996894f2df7024e8becf5e8a3f1c2789455ecd\"},{\"title\":\"A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting[v1] | Preprints.org\",\"url\":\"https://www.preprints.org/manuscript/202506.2479/v1\"},{\"title\":\"A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2506.22634\"},{\"title\":\"A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting -\",\"url\":\"https://www.authorea.com/users/921073/articles/1309702-a-rigorous-error-bound-for-the-tg-kernel-in-prime-counting\"},{\"title\":\"Analytic Number Theory\",\"url\":\"https://www.claymath.org/library/proceedings/cmip07c.pdf\"},{\"title\":\"13281 PDFs | Review articles in ANALYTIC NUMBER THEORY\",\"url\":\"https://www.researchgate.net/topic/Analytic-Number-Theory/publications\"},{\"title\":\"Reproducing Kernel Spaces and Applications (Operator Theory: Advances and Applications): Alpay, Daniel: 9783034894302: Amazon.com: Books\",\"url\":\"https://www.amazon.com/Reproducing-Kernel-Spaces-Applications-Operator/dp/3034894309\"},{\"title\":\"Analytic number theory - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytic_number_theory\"},{\"title\":\"arXiv:2308.03126v2 [math.NT] 9 Aug 2023 BULLETIN (New Series) OF THE\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2308.03126\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, I found relevant information about the work by Kilictas and Alpay:\n\nThe paper establishes rigorous error bounds for prime counting using a truncated Gaussian (TG) kernel in the explicit formula framework. The main theorem proves that the approximation error remains globally below 1/2 for all sufficiently large arguments, guaranteeing exact computation of π(x) through simple rounding, without relying on unproven hypotheses.\n\nThe TG kernel construction employs Gaussian-like test functions with compact support, engineered with vanishing moments to eliminate main terms. For x with 10^8 decimal digits, they demonstrate that only ~1200 nontrivial zeta zeros suffice to achieve the error bound, enabling computation in seconds on modern hardware - a dramatic improvement over classical methods.\n\nKey contributions include: (1) Explicit tail truncation bounds using Taylor remainder analysis, showing exponential decay; (2) Zero-sum truncation error bounds via unconditional density estimates; (3) Rigorous treatment of trivial zero contributions.\n\nThe paper was published on arXiv as arXiv:2506.22634 in June 2025 and authored by Bugra Kilictas and Faruk Alpay.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"8dacc815-7960-4415-8dd2-e27d32e7a675","timestamp":"2026-04-04T16:41:08.479Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2331dbad-dcf6-4c86-9812-d6f64cbb2811","userType":"external","entrypoint":"sdk-cli","cwd":"/apps/aplikacijos/prime-research","sessionId":"9a4d0a1c-3aab-4791-8f3d-2b88c6fa29b8","version":"2.1.92","gitBranch":"main","slug":"iridescent-kindling-sparkle"}
    {"parentUuid":"8dacc815-7960-4415-8dd2-e27d32e7a675","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ac31b9f8e30a62569","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CM6Tx7UtLriBXnZHvXtTES","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a comprehensive picture. Let me compile the report.\n\nHere is a comprehensive report of findings from the 2025-2026 literature search:\n\n---\n\n## HIGH-RELEVANCE FINDINGS\n\n### 1. TG Kernel Method for Exact Prime Counting (MOST IMPORTANT)\n**Paper:** \"A Rigorous Error Bound for the TG Kernel in Prime Counting\"\n**Authors:** Bugra Kilictas, Faruk Alpay\n**ArXiv:** [2506.22634](https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.22634) (June 2025)\n\nThis paper claims that using a truncated Gaussian kernel in the explicit formula framework, the error in approximating pi(x) stays below 1/2, enabling exact computation via rounding. The key claim: for x with 10^8 decimal digits, only ~1200 nontrivial zeta zeros suffice. The TG kernel has rapid spectral decay (faster than 1/|t|^3), so high zeros contribute negligibly. The truncation height T relates to alpha = sqrt(ln(x)), meaning the number of zeros needed scales roughly as O(polylog(x)).\n\n**Critical caveats:** The paper explicitly defers formal complexity analysis. It does not provide a theorem statement for total time complexity, does not address the cost of computing each zeta zero (which is itself nontrivial), and the \"1200 zeros\" claim needs careful scrutiny. If the zero-computation cost is included, the total complexity may still be substantial. The paper is not yet peer-reviewed.\n\n**Relevance to project:** If verified, this could be a dramatic improvement over summing O(sqrt(x)) zeros. The key question is whether the claimed O(polylog) zero count holds rigorously, and what the per-zero computation cost is. This deserves immediate investigation.\n\n### 2. Algorithms for Computing p_n\n**Paper:** \"A Note on Algorithms for Computing p_n\"\n**Author:** Ansh Aggarwal\n**ArXiv: